@flexiarg math-strategy/property-of-object-result
@title Property-of-Object-Result Family
@sigils [▣/質]
@keywords property, regularity, rigidity, bound, asymptotic, family-parent, domain-specific
@audience mathematicians, paper-writers, pattern-classifiers
@tone classification / heuristic
@factor Discernment (paññā)
@references [math-informal/estimate-by-bounding math-informal/monotone-approximation math-informal/pass-to-a-subsequence]

! conclusion:
  Your paper establishes a property of a *fixed* object — its regularity, its
  rigidity, an asymptotic, a bound, a stability estimate — rather than asserting
  the object exists or relating it to another.

  + context: An object is given (a PDE solution, a measure, a representation,
    a numerical scheme, a physical state); the question is what it does. The
    object's existence is taken for granted (or established earlier); the
    paper's contribution is properties that follow.

  + IF:
      The paper's main contribution can be expressed as "the solution has
      such-and-such regularity", or "any solution with property P must vanish",
      or "the asymptotic behaviour is X", or "we bound this quantity by Y".

  + HOWEVER:
      Property-of-object is the *smaller and more domain-specific family* in
      our pilot (≈ 8 % of papers — see
      `futon3/holes/excursions/E-math-prototype-pilot.md` Phase 2). Many of its
      leaves are domain-tied (PDE regularity, measure-theoretic decay, group-
      action rigidity). The family parent serves as the umbrella; the
      domain-specific leaves accrete as we tag more papers.

  + THEN:
      1. Identify the property class — regularity / asymptotic / rigidity /
         bound / decay / stability.
      2. Locate or note the absence of a domain-specific leaf for that class.
         (If absent, this is the seed for a new leaf flexiarg.)
      3. Identify the *witness* of the property — explicit estimate, decay
         rate, regularity exponent, vanishing condition.

  + BECAUSE:
      Property-of-object papers do "what-it-does work" rather than asserting
      existence or relating structures. They are heavily domain-shaped — a
      PDE-regularity result and a measure-theoretic-rigidity result share the
      family form but almost no analytic technique. The family parent gives
      the coarse classifier; *domain-specific leaves are expected to grow over
      time*, and their accretion is itself a signal of corpus coverage.

  + MEMBER-PATTERNS:
      member[math-informal/estimate-by-bounding]              # general bounds
      member[math-informal/monotone-approximation]            # asymptotic
      member[math-informal/pass-to-a-subsequence]             # convergence / asymptotic
      # Domain-specific leaves (to be authored as the corpus grows):
      # math-informal/regularity-and-asymptotics (PDE-flavoured)
      # math-informal/rigidity-from-decay-conditions  (analytic-rigidity-flavoured)

  + EXEMPLAR-PAPERS:
      exemplar[arxiv-2604.20798v1]   # PDE solution regularity + edge singularity
      exemplar[arxiv-2604.20794v1]   # Hardy-uncertainty / rigidity
      # The pilot only saw 2 papers in this family; the leaves are placeholder
      # until the next ≈ 25-paper extension expands the tail.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
      next[Identify the property class and check for a domain-specific leaf.]
      next[If no leaf fits, note the gap as a candidate new flexiarg.]
      next[Cross-check: is the property quantitative (with a number / rate) or qualitative (with / without)?]
